  <subsection xml:id="subsection-difference-of-squares">
    <title>Difference of Squares</title>
    
    <example>
      <title>Intro Examples</title>
      <p>
        When multiplying two binomials that are almost the same, except for one having a positive sign and one having a negative, there is a special pattern. Observe the expansion,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>(x-2)(x+2) \amp = x^2 + 2x - 2x - 4</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x^2 - 4</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        Notice that the middle terms <m>2x</m> and <m>-2x</m> cancel out.
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>(x-6)(x+6) \amp = x^2 + 6x - 6x - 36</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x^2 - 36</mrow>
        <mrow>(x+10)(x-10) \amp = x^2 + 10x - 10x - 100</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = x^2 - 100</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        In general, when expanding an expression of the form <m>(x-a)(x+a)</m> (where the two numbers are opposites of each other), the middle two terms always cancel out, because they are opposites of each other. The result is <m>x</m> squared, minus the number <m>a</m> squared.
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      In general,
    </p>
    <me>
      (a+b)(a-b) = a^2 - b^2
    </me>
    <p>
      This identity for expanding can be thought of in reverse, as an identity for factoring,
    </p>
    <me>
      \boxed{a^2 - b^2 = (a-b)(a+b)}
    </me>
    <p>
      In other words, for an expression of the form <m>a^2 - b^2</m> (where there are two things being squared, and they're subtracted), it can be factored as <m>(a-b)(a+b)</m>. It's called <em>difference of squares</em>, <q>difference</q> because of the minus sign, and <q>squares</q> because both terms are perfect squares.
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <p>
        For example, <m>x^2-9</m> is a difference of squares, because it's <m>x</m> squared, and 9 is <m>3^2</m>, so,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>x^2-9 = (x-3)(x+3)</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    
